flowRoot.flowPara: • Cortical rhythms in auditory cortex reflect the note rate of heard music. (Doelling & Poeppel, 2015)
• Are these rhythms truly oscillating or do they simply mirror the rhythmic input?
• Here, we tease apart these two posibilities by studying phase lags at a range of frequencies. The two models should make different predictions which can be borne out in our analysis.

flowRoot.flowPara: • The two models in practice look very similar. Both peak activity with new input
• Oscillator model provides important theoretical benefits (e.g. prediction) that the evoked model cannot
• Probing the relationship between the phase of sync and the frequency of stimulation will allow for model distinction and to see which model best represents human data.

text.tspan: MEG results are more consistent with the oscillator model

flowRoot.flowPara: Wilson-Cowan (WC) Model

In two MEG experiments, participants listened to 3 clips each from 3 songs chosen for their note rate. Exp 1: 0.5, 5 and 8 notes per second (nps). Exp 2: 0.7, 1, and 1.5 nps. We found that nonmusicians entrained to music at the note rate only ≥1 nps. Here, we use this data to analyze how note rates affect the phase of synchronization and use two models to uncover the most likely mechanism of synchrony.

flowPara.flowSpan: The two models, evoked and oscillator, show two distinct phase patterns: spread around the circle vs phase consistency.

flowRoot.flowPara: • The MEG data shows more phase consistency as predicted by the wilson-cowan model.

• Interestingly, both WC and MEG show synchrony to fastest 8 nps at a different phase. This could represent a second mechanism of synchrony similar to steady state response (SSR) at higher frequencies.
Hypothesis:
The oscillator model will track stimuli at a consistent phase regardless of frequency. If auditory cortical rhythms are oscillating as well, they should show a similar phase spread.

flowRoot.flowPara: Model output shows high synchrony to the stimulus but the phase of synchrony rotates with increasing note rate. Clips at the same note rate show similar phase, suggesting that in an evoked model the phase is dependent at least in part on note rate and likely the peak response of the kernel.

Model output synchrony varies as note rate moves away from the oscillator's resting frequency but the phase is consistent. Interesting here is the 8 nps condition which regains high synchrony at a separate phase and may reflect a different mechanism similar to steady-state response (SSR).
We chose parameters for the model based on the literature to be at or near an oscillatory state. Then, we incorporated the stimulus envelope as a driving force to the excitatory population
Example model outputs

The MEG data confirms what we found in our original paper with a different analysis tool, cerebro-acoustic coherence (CACoh): synchrony occurs only above 1 nps. The phase of synchrony still largely points in the same direction regardless of frequency with the exception of 8 nps. The phase points in a different direction than our Wilson-Cowan model but the overall pattern of phase consistency across note rates is much more consistent with the oscillator model rather than evoked.
1. Doelling, K.B. & Poeppel, D. (2015) Cortical entrainment to music and its modulation by expertise. PNAS, 112 (45) E6233-42.
2. Wilson, H.R. & Cowan, J. (1972). Excitatory and Inhibitory interactions in localized populations of model neurons. Biophysical Journal, 12 (1) 1-24.
